  RFC6919 [label="RFC6919
Further Key Words for Use in RFCs to
Indicate Requirement Levels
2013", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6919.html", target="_top", tooltip="RFC 2119 defines a standard set of key words for describing requirements of a specification. Many IETF documents have found that these words cannot accurately capture the nuanced requirements of their specification. This document defines additional key words that can be used to address alternative requirements scenarios. Authors who follow these guidelines should incorporate this phrase near the beginning of their document: The key words MUST (BUT WE KNOW YOU WON\'T), SHOULD CONSIDER, REALLY SHOULD NOT, OUGHT TO, WOULD PROBABLY, MAY WISH TO, COULD, POSSIBLE, and MIGHT in this document are to be interpreted as described in RFC 6919."];
  RFC6919 -> rev_cites;
  RFC7165 [label="RFC7165
Use Cases and Requirements for JSON
Object Signing and Encryption (JOSE)
2014", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC7165.html", target="_top", tooltip="Many Internet applications have a need for object-based security mechanisms in addition to security mechanisms at the network layer or transport layer.  For many years, the Cryptographic Message Syntax (CMS) has provided a binary secure object format based on ASN.1.  Over time, binary object encodings such as ASN.1 have become less common than text-based encodings, such as the JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).  This document defines a set of use cases and requirements for a secure object format encoded using JSON, drawn from a variety of application security mechanisms currently in development."];
  RFC7165 -> rev_cites;
  RFC7435 [label="RFC7435
Opportunistic Security: Some Protection
Most of the Time
2014", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC7435.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document defines the concept Opportunistic Security in the context of communications protocols.  Protocol designs based on Opportunistic Security use encryption even when authentication is not available, and use authentication when possible, thereby removing barriers to the widespread use of encryption on the Internet."];
  RFC7435 -> rev_cites;
  RFC7508 [label="RFC7508
Securing Header Fields with S/MIME
2015", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC7508.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes how the S/MIME protocol can be extended in order to secure message header fields defined in RFC 5322.  This technology provides security services such as data integrity, non-repudiation, and confidentiality.  This extension is referred to as 'Secure Headers'."];
  RFC7508 -> rev_cites;
  RFC7672 [label="RFC7672
SMTP Security via Opportunistic DNS-
Based Authentication of Named Entities
(DANE) Transport Layer Security (TLS)
2015", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC7672.html", target="_top", tooltip="This memo describes a downgrade-resistant protocol for SMTP transport security between Message Transfer Agents (MTAs), based on the DNS-Based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) TLSA DNS record.  Adoption of this protocol enables an incremental transition of the Internet email backbone to one using encrypted and authenticated Transport Layer Security (TLS)."];
